<p style="text-align:justify;">rather scarlet berry which is of a p<span class="AddHand-author">l</span>easant flavour: and the branches are used by the Indians along with <span class="AddHand-author">the</span> white Spruce and Hemlock in their sweats and in fomentations<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The Juniper is never found but on the borders of the Lakes in pure Sand or Gravel and even some times on the Solid Rock: it is So generally known as to need no description &#8211; however I have Remarked one Singular quality it possesses, which is, when no obstruction intervenes it always Spreads in a circle<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The Honeysuckle is very Scarce and comes far Short of the beauty and Richness it attains in more temperate climates<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="DelHand-author">Osiers and Willows never come to any perfection</span>  There is a Species of Willow the bark of which is Red on the Young Shoots or branches, but on those of two or three Years standing it becomes brown and towards the Root gray<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The Indians take off the Outer bark carefully, the inner, which is of a Yellowish colour the scrape from the wood and chewed or pounded apply to ulcerous wounds with an effect beyond any Salve or Ointment I have ever seen<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>hey also dry it and smoke it mixed with Tobacco when at a loss for their favourite herb call'd Sackacomi<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The bush cranberry is a beautiful Shrub which grows to 5 or 6 feet high, the Stalk is a light grey the leaves heart shaped indented and of a</p>

